03909nam a22004455i 9780773568273DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735682737 a10.1515/97807735682732doi  a(DE-B1597)655348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJN5452bS22 2000eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.9451 aSabetti, Filippo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSearch for Good Government :bUnderstanding the Paradox of Italian Democracy /cFilippo Sabetti. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tItalian Politics: School for Good Government -- tConstitutional Knowledge and Alternative Constitutional Designs in the Making of Italy -- tThe Creation of the Italian State -- tThe Constitutional Design That Did Not Happen -- tHow the System Worked in Republican Italy: Institutional Learning and Constraints -- tExpectations and Results in Public Service Delivery -- tProblem Solving by Central Planning -- tThe War on Crime as a Fight for Good Government -- tThe Mafia and the Antimafia -- tThe Political Economy of Crime and Punishment -- tWhy People Are Not Culturally or Path Dependently Doomed to Bad Government -- tThe Search for the Real Montegrano -- tPath Dependence, Civic Culture, and Differential Government Performance -- tGood Government: The Elusive Dependent Variable -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSabetti argues that poor government performance in contemporary Italy has been an unintended consequence of attempts to craft institutions for good - or democratic - government. He shows that, contrary to the conventional wisdom, a chief problem in contemporary Italy is not the absence of the rule of law but, rather, the presence of rule by law or too many laws. A principal conclusion of his study is that postwar Italian politics can best be understood as a laboratory for revealing how and why a search for good government can generate antithetical and counter intentional results. The Italian experience has important implications for all those who aspire to be self-governing - as opposed to state-governed - for it shows what people can do to enhance human cooperation in collective-action dilemmas and suggests the probable results if "democracy" continues to be identified with parliamentary government and representative assemblies rather than with the universality of the village or the local community. The Search for Good Government changes our understanding of postwar Italian politics and provides new ways to evaluate the impact of the political changes that have occurred since 1992, arguing for a perceptual shift in the way we think about politics and the educative role of public institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356827340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568273423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568273/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles